---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const mount = `import { mountField } from '@forces-ui/elements';

// creates a fixed full-viewport canvas, starts the engine, returns the handle
const field = mountField({ accent: '#4da3ff', render: 'dots' });

// …later
field.destroy();   // stops the loop AND removes the canvas it created`;

const create = `import { createField } from 'forces-ui';

const canvas = document.querySelector('canvas');
const field = createField(canvas, {
  accent: '#4da3ff',
  density: 1,
  attention: false,
  causality: false,
});

// the field reads every [data-body] element on the page.
// after you add or remove bodies, rescan:
field.scan();`;

const custom = `import { createField } from 'forces-ui';

// a custom force is just an object with token + apply(b, p, env).
// register it on a fresh field by composing your own — or use the catalog.
// (advanced) see the Force type in the types reference.`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="forces-ui — Vanilla / core guide"
  description="Use the forces-ui engine directly: mountField() to create a managed canvas, or createField() to drive your own. Both return the FieldHandle. Zero runtime dependencies."
>
  <header class="docs-hero">
    <p class="kicker">Guides</p>
    <h1>Vanilla &amp; the <span class="accent">core engine</span></h1>
    <p class="lede">
      Skip the wrappers and drive the engine yourself — either with a canvas it manages for you,
      or one you own. The core is zero-dependency TypeScript.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <div class="pkg-grid">
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @forces-ui/elements">npm i @forces-ui/elements</code>
        <span>for <code>mountField()</code> — it creates and manages the canvas</span>
      </div>
      <div class="pkg">
        <code class="install" data-copy="npm i forces-ui">npm i forces-ui</code>
        <span>for <code>createField()</code> — when you own the canvas</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>mountField — a managed canvas</h2>
    <p>
      The framework-free imperative mount. It creates a fixed full-viewport canvas, starts the
      engine, and returns the <a href="/docs/api/handle">FieldHandle</a>. Its
      <code>destroy()</code> also removes the canvas it made.
    </p>
    <pre class="code"><code>{mount}</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>createField — your own canvas</h2>
    <p>
      When you want to place and size the canvas yourself, hand it to <code>createField</code>.
      You get the same handle. This is the lowest-level entry point; everything else wraps it.
    </p>
    <pre class="code"><code>{create}</code></pre>
    <div class="callout">
      <b>The canvas is decorative.</b> Position it fixed behind your content
      (<code>position: fixed; inset: 0; z-index: 0; pointer-events: none</code>) and mark it
      <code>aria-hidden</code>. Reduced motion is honoured automatically, and the loop pauses
      when the tab is backgrounded.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Custom forces</h2>
    <p>
      A force is just <code>{'{ token, apply(b, p, env) }'}</code>. The engine never special-cases
      any single force — they all implement the same contract, so you can author your own against
      the <a href="/docs/api/types">Force type</a>.
    </p>
    <pre class="code"><code>{custom}</code></pre>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
